watermark.note: TUMBA + beehive surrounded by flying bees

supportDesc.foliation: Modern foliation in pencil. Error in foliation: instad of f. 47; f. 139 skipped (no gap in text), named 265 or 264. -nibus nostris et elemento

collation.signatures: Quire signatures in roman numerals on quires 18, 20, and 21. All quires probably had signatures, but these have been lost due to trimming.

p.note: Top of page in dark ink by a 18th or 19th c. hand: 1734 års Kat. Theol. in folio No 43; and further down by the same hand: Misale Olomucense (these words have also been written in pencil above the words in ink).

binding.p:
Post-medieval binding, possibly 16th or 17th century. Redish-brown leather over wooded boards. The boards are shaped around the edges. 5 pairs of raised bands and endbands Metal catch plates on and one remaining piece of plate on . , blind stamped: Missale olomucensis
. , stamped in gold: A 177.
binding.decoNote: Elaborate tooling in the shape of frames filled with geometric and vegetative ornaments. The tooling seems to have been gilded, but only traces remain. Medaltion in the middle of , but the motive is no longer visible. On the frames also contain small medalions with human faces.
binding.condition: Leather covering worn and damaged. Clasps missing. Leather on parts of the cover and spine renovated with new leather. Old library signa removed from spine and attached to .

history.origin: Olomouc , 15th century. The precense of the patron saints of Olomouc together with the glossing in Czech indicates Olmouc as the place of origin.
history.provenance: The manuscript was most likely take from Olomouc and brought to Sweden as war booty during the Thirty Years’ War. It is believed to be the manuscript listed n Vossius’ catalogue from 1649 (U 202:1), p. 69, as Missale. On there are three notes glued to the margin. These were orginally attached to the spine. Two of these notes contain signa, the first that of Hammarsköld's catalogue from the 19th century (U 133): e. 30. 5. 2.; the second one the signum from the catalogue of 1734 (U 125e): 43? Missale (listed in the catalogue as Theol. in fol. 43). The only signum on the is the current signum A 177.

note.p: The calendar starts with Circumcisio Domini (Jan. 1) and ends with Silvester papa (Dec. 31).
Names of the months written both in Latin and Czech.
Notable saints: Cyrillus and Methodius; Sigismund, Stanislaus; Vitus; Procopius; Ludmilla, Weneclas; Cordula; translacio Ludmille, Quinque fratrum.

watermark.term: Oxhead above single line rod with flower on top.
watermark.note: The ink on the leaves is very dark and dense, which makes the watermarks difficult to identify. The oxhead is most clearly visible. The second watermark is quite large but thus far completely unidentifiable. The third watermark is a large complex shape, with the only identfiable feature being a rod with a trefoil on top.

watermark.term: Rod with trefoil, part of larger motif.

supportDesc.condition: The paper is dirty and stained, possibly moldy. Outer margins trimmed with loss of text in the marginal additions. The text block has been rapaired with paper strips in the inner margin and on all the margins; a hole caused by fire damage on has been rapired with paper on with some loss of text.

layout.note: Ruling and guidelines in dark ink.

p.note: Top margin in brown ink by a modern hand: Missale. Outer margin: 3 stickers with old library signa glued to the page. These have probably been removed from the spine. The stickers read (from top to bottom): Missa- ; e 50. 5. 2.; 43 ? Missale.

Sporadic additions in the margins in dark ink by one or more medieval hands. The additions range from single words to short phrases and seem to be both in Latin and Old Czech (for the latter see e.g. bottom margin on : blahoslavení).

decoDesc.p: Main text in black ink, capitals touched in red, rubrics in red.
decoDesc.decoNote: : plain P over 8 lines in red. : Plain R over 6 lines in red with flourishing, counter space in yellow. : Puzzle initial V over 4 lines, outlined in dark ink, couloured red and brown. : Plain S over 4 lines (+ extending below the line) in red with flourishing, counter space in yellow. : Plain flourished B over 5 lines, outlined in black ink, touched in red. : T over 7 lines. Outlined in ink but not coloured. : space reserved for inital. : plain initials over 1-4 lines in red. Sometimes the counterspace is filled with a yellow-brown colour.

: full page image the Crucifixion of Jesus. Christ on the cross surrounded by Mary and John. Ink and watercolours. Outlined in brown ink. Main colours: brown, blue, red, and pink. Background painted green.
